n): from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Ha(i)mon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. It frequently developed excrescent <i>-d</i>, giving <i>Hamond</i>, <i>Haimund</i>, and <i>Hawmond</i>. Alternatively, the name could derive from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamund</i> (Old Norse <i>Hámundr</i>, composed of the elements <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’), which may have been used in Normandy and in 12th-century eastern England, but the former explanation is more likely. The surname was sometimes confused with   Almond   and   Ammon  .","English: in the Bradford area of Yorkshire, the name is a shortened form of <b>Ormondroyd</b>, formerly <i>Hamondesrode</i>, from a lost place in Birstall (Yorkshire), named with the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Hamon</i> (1 above) + Middle English <i>roid</i>, a southern Yorkshire pronunciation of Old English <i>rod</i> ‘clearing’.","Irish: generally an importation from England, but occasionally an adopted name for <b>Mac Ámoinn</b>, see   McCammon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hammonds","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Hammond  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Almond","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Almund</i>, in which Old English <i>Æthelmund</i> ‘noble protector’ and <i>Ealhmund</i> ‘temple protector’ have coalesced.","variant of   Allman   and   Allmand   both meaning ‘German’, assimilated by folk etymology to the vocabulary word denoting the tree."]},{"name":"Hammett","meanings":["English (southwestern England, especialy Devon): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hamet</i>, a pet form of ancient Germanic <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond   1)."]},{"name":"Hamon","meanings":["Breton, French, and English (Channel Islands): from the Breton, Old French, Middle English personal name <i>Hamon</i>, the oblique case form of the ancient Germanic <i>Ha(i)mo</i>, a short form of various compound names beginning with <i>haim</i> ‘home’. See also   Hammond  ."]},{"name":"Hamlin","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, from the Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Hamelin</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Hamo</i> (see   Hammond  ).","French: variant of   Hamelin   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","Americanized form of Finnish <b>Hämäläinen</b> (see   Hamalainen  )."]},{"name":"Hampson","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): patronymic from the Norman personal name <i>Hamo</i>, <i>Hamon</i> (see   Hammond  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAmhsaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Amhsach</i>’ a byname meaning ‘mercenary soldier’ or ‘messenger’, from the adjective <i>amhasach</i> ‘aggressive’."]},{"name":"Haimes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Yacov, Yosef.","English: variant, with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, of <b>Haime</b>, of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Haim</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Haimo</i>, from <i>haim-</i> ‘home’), often Latinized as <i>Hamo</i>. Compare   Hammond  .","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."]},{"name":"Hammon","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Ken): variant of   Hammond  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":35,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Hammond was born in 1347, in Checkley, Staffordshire, England, his father, Adam de Peshale II, was 71 and his mother, Joan de Eyton, was 48. He married Alice Harley about 1375, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1399, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1347–1399":"1347–1399","1322–1387":"1322–1387","1328–1387":"1328–1387","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1349–1389":"1349–1389","1375–1435":"1375–1435","1277–1346":"1277–1346","1300–1383":"1300–1383","before 1322":"enne 1322","1330":"1330","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1349":"1349","1347":"1347","1435":"1435","1346":"1346","1389":"1389","1399":"1399","1300":"1300","1322":"1322","1277":"1277","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","about 1375":"umbes 1375","1328":"1328","Belper, Derbyshire, England":"Belper, Derbyshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cresswell, Woodhorn, Northumberland, England":"Woodhorn, Northumberland, England","Checkley, Staffordshire, England":"Checkley, Staffordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1347–1399":"1347–1399","1322–1387":"1322–1387","1328–1387":"1328–1387","1328–Female":"1328–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1349–1389":"1349–1389","1375–1435":"1375–1435","1277–1346":"1277–1346","1300–1383":"1300–1383","before 1322":"ennen vuotta 1322","1330":"1330","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1349":"1349","1347":"1347","1435":"1435","1346":"1346","1389":"1389","1399":"1399","1300":"1300","1322":"1322","1277":"1277","1387":"1387","1375":"1375","about 1375":"noin 1375","1328":"1328","Belper, Derbyshire, England":"Belper, Derbyshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cresswell, Woodhorn, Northumberland, England":"Woodhorn, Northumberland, England","Checkley, Staffordshire, England":"Checkley, Staffordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England"},"fr":{"1347